// ========== WEBSITES ========== \\
1. https://mmv.wagyourtail.xyz/ (for older Forge versions).
2. https://mappings.dev/ (for newer Forge versions).
Note: I used mmv.wagyourtail.xyz sometimes for Minecraft Forge 1.12.2 mappings, because mappings.dev didn't help.
3. http://github.com/ (yeah it is truly helpful, you can also download libraries or check other's work).
4. https://www.virustotal.com/ (use this to scan files, ensuring the safety of the equipment).
5. https://www.javadecompilers.com/ (others may say you're a coward, but do you care?)
6. https://dogbolt.org/ (decompiling binary files, .dll/.so/.dylib/.exe...).
Note: You can use IDA (Interactive Disassembler), it has more features than dogbolt. Or you can try Ghidra.

// ========== TOOLS ========== \\
1. IDE (Integrated Development Environment). The most common is IntelliJ IDEA.
2. JD-GUI (Java Decompiler Graphical User Interface). Again, people may call you a coward, but do you care if you're the one getting results?
3. HMCL (Hello! Minecraft Launcher) by Glavo. This is a famous Minecraft launcher.
4. MCreator (basic tool for modding), you can use this to help you create a workspace. So you don't have to worry about gradle's setup.
5. One Drive (actually this is a service). It will help you store your workspace, create backups, etc. You can also use Github.
6. Cheat engine(s) (if you are working with native level, but if you have the ability to deal with C++, I think you don't need these lists anymore).
